GLOBAL
- Sanctuary law: active healing wards are protected in all five cities; violence
  in a healing sanctuary is a serious civic offense regardless of grievance
- Healing services: temples charge sliding scale or expect donation; emergency
  treatment during flood/fire/plague is typically free under disaster law
- Funerary rites: vary by race and tradition; Khenari death-ledger protocols
  are the most precise; pyramid corridor traditions use solar/lunar frameworks;
  coastal cities use sea-release rites
- Oath arbitration: temple witnesses are legally recognized in all cities;
  oaths sworn before a temple adjudicator have standing in civil tribunals
~
MIDGAARD
- Temple of the Resounding Heart: frames city history as collective penance for
  uncounted dead (Conclave era); maintains memorial rolls; runs seismological
  watch (Cinderteeth monitoring); pilgrim routes converge here
- Temple priests are instructed not to speak against the Lantern Registry
  publicly, but privately most support the Reckoning faction's aims
- The Temple's Bell Watch (two bells after midnight) signals memorial, not
  alarm; visitors should know the difference before panicking
~
KOWLOON
- Temple Circle healers wear undyed linen; answer to no secular authority while
  treating patients — a privilege from the original Neon Covenant, never revoked
- Temple Circle handles funerary rites without discrimination of origin or
  faction; this neutrality was established during the Ashfall years and is
  considered sacred
- Oath arbitration services available at Temple Circle offices; jade seal
  not required for temple-witnessed oaths, only for emergency civic powers
~
KIESS
- Temple of Concord houses the Shrine of the Compact Flame; the flame symbolizes
  the founding pact and is never extinguished
- Compact theologians preserve fragments of Keeper-of-Measure survey prayers,
  repurposed as civic benedictions; some match inscriptions found on Northern
  Pyramid threshold stones
- Temple delegates to Rakuen advise on whether Rakuen's emergency labor drafts
  cross into coercive-warrant territory Kiess's charter prohibits
~
RAKUEN
- Bloom Pavilion (rebuilt three times, still standing): where stewardship
  rotations are announced and founding rites performed
- Promise Stones in every neighborhood; defacing one is a serious social offense
- The founding's three civic conditions: Enoughness (food/water guarantees),
  Seen Labor (honored maintenance work), Ritual Repair (public rites for grief
  and reconciliation) — all are invoked in temple services
~
MAFDET
- Shrine of the First Claw: not a conventional temple but a civic-judicial
  facility; oath-sealing, dispute arbitration, and trade oath enforcement
- The guardian Mafdet is not a deity of comfort but of enforcement: the shrine
  does not bless commerce, it punishes betrayal
- Jackal Synod (pyramid corridor funerary authority) has never been strong
  enough in Mafdet to challenge the Shrine; theological tension persists
- Swift Court operates on three-tide judgment principle; final, no appeal
  except to full Shrine council for inter-city treaty matters
~
